<br>
Proccessor -AMD Athlon xp 1900+<br>
<br>
Video- PNY GeForce 3 Ti500 64 DDR<br>
<br>
Sound- Creative Platinum 5.1<br>
<br>
Monitor- Viewsonic 19in E95<br>
<br>
Power Supply- AMD cg-350w<br>
<br>
Printer- Epson c80<br>
<br>
Speakers- Klipsch 5.1<br>
<br>
RAM- Pc 2100 DDR 512meg x3<br>
<br>
Cd-Rw- elements 24x10x40<br>
<br>
DVD- cyberdrive 16x40<br>
<br>
1.5 floppy- sony mpf920<br>
<br>
Modem- Motorola 56k pci<br>
<br>
Keyboard/mouse- logitech cordless freedom optical (mouse keyboard bundle<br>
<br>
Hard-drive- Have a question, should we get two?  a small one for swap files etc and the other for main hard-drive duties?  And if so how do we set it up and will mobo handle it?<br>
<br>
Heat-sink cooling for proc- any advice here?<br>
<br>
<br>
Looking at a total cost pre-shipping in the 2800 range...least thats what my math is showing.<br>
<br>
<br>
Also would it matter to get a dual proc mobo @ 1300mhz or stay single with faster proc with xp 1900+?<br>
<br>
This is a &quot;dream machine&quot; I am making for her so any and all advice appreciated. <p>

<p align=center><img src="http://www.slackman.com/sunrunners/shots/mismortsig.JPG"</p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/udunkk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Dunkk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 233<br> <font color=#E9D756>(12/18/01 2:21:42 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://dunkamar.50megs.com/JB.gif height=160 width=160></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Making a new computer...help please:)</span><hr size=1> gEEZZEEE ! <br>
<br>
/drool<br>
<br>
If you are concerned about keeping the unit cool, fit the case with a &quot;bay&quot; fan. These type of units fit into a slot for cd-roms and usually have 2 fans for sucking in air- then the fan in back that blows out the air gets some help... p.s. put the greatest distance poss between these two fans- that way you move the max air within the case. And if you really wanted to go crazy you could get a RAM cooler too- just incase you are worried about her 1.5gigs of Ram heating up!<br>
<br>
If You have the cooling power in that case, I'd say run a hott 1.9 single processor.  Besides, Im not sure How or If EQ can utilize a 2 processor setup. But I tell ya with that much CPU, Ram and Vieo Card Power I sure hope that her internet connection isn't dial-up. LOL<br>
<br>
I saw your spec on a modem... just hope that she has DSL or else you are wasting a large amount of money due to the bottleneck on bandwidth.<br>
<br>
Oh and IMO- it's better to have one large drive. The only thing I use my secondary HDD for is a place to keep my ghost image file and some old movie trailers and misc data.<br>
<br>
have FUN !<br>
<br>
p.s. My Advise was asuming that she is using this PC for EQ... that may not be the case as you didn't mention what the PC was being used for.  If it's not going to be a gaming machine then my advise would change accordingly. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/udunkk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Dunkk</A> at: 12/18/01 2:37:20 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ucoasttoast.showPublicProfile?language=EN>CoastToast</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 346<br> <font color=#E9D756>(12/18/01 2:42:11 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> hmm</span><hr size=1> Keep the single processor setup. Few games or programs utilize dual processors (quake3, RtCW, linux). So you are better off with single.<br>
<br>
With 2 HD's i think you can use RAID, but I'm not fimiliar with it at all. But you can setup the HD's so the first can have the main files on it (windows and games; you should make it a SCSI for good performance), and the second can run backups and such (EIDE would work fine).<br>
