<br>
ASUS makes a good board. Stick with them.<br>
<br>
The case really doesn't matter as long as it's large.<br>
<br>
Processor...here's the big one. Why in the hell does anyone buy AMD?! They're overheated, overblown, underbuilt pieces of shit. Yeah, they're cheaper than an Intel, but are we really going to believe that it's only because they're competing? Pick up an Intel P4 running a couple of hundred Mhz slower than your AMD and it'll blow the faster AMD out of the water. The people running AMD processors are the same people keeping &quot;Friends&quot; on the air.<br>
<br>
The GeForce 3 Ti500 is the ONLY way to go these days. Rather than PNY though, have a look at the Gainward series. They're a tad bit faster than the rest in the memory department.<br>
<br>
Get an Audigy. You won't regret it.<br>
<br>
Viewsonic makes a sweet monitor. I use them and Princeton exclusively.<br>
<br>
As long as your power supply has enough connections, it should work.<br>
<br>
Printer? We don't need no stinking printer! Epson's not a bad choice if you're gonna get one though.<br>
<br>
Klipsch. Sweet. If not, Bose.<br>
<br>
RAM. Drop the AMD and go Intel, nab RAMBUS stuff. Get a board that supports at least 4Gb and start with 2Gb. If you ever need more, you have the room.<br>
<br>
CD-RW. I'm partial to the HP burners. I've just been using them excusively for 6+ years though....<br>
<br>
DVD. Why bother on the computer? Save the money for a bigger TV. I tried watching a movie on my computer one time...it fucked with AoE.<br>
<br>
Floppy drives are shit.<br>
<br>
Modem? Who needs them anymore? Definitely stay PCI if you have to have one though. Throw a 10/100 NIC card in as well. 3Com makes a great one.<br>
<br>
Logitech has a sweeeet wireless KB/Mouse combo.<br>
<br>
Hard Drive. ASUS makes a series of boards with a Promise ATA-100 controller on board behind the standard IDE connectors. This allows up to 8 drives, rather than the standard 4. I would suggest a small (40G or smaller) system drive for the OS and programs, and a pair of matched drives for data (around 120Gb). You can put one of each matched drives on a channel of the Promise controller and mirror them. If done correctly, you can basically negate any data loss for the rest of your life.<br>
<br>
Heat sinks? They should be included.<br>
<br>
Oh well, that's just the way I've built mine, and it makes those AMD based custom jobs look like old Packard Bell boxes.<br>
<br>
Tovectris <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ubridgecrusher.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bridgecrusher</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_greenspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 117<br> <font color=#E9D756>(12/19/01 9:04:13 am)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Hehe...</span><hr size=1> I have to disagree with the comparison between AMD and P4.  In actuality the P4 is clocked a whole lot faster than an AMD.  The 1900+ number listed is just for comparison sake for an uninformed consumer - the AMD actually run at far less clock cycles per second.  The quality of the silicon is the same, with the P4 having a thermal cutoff switch (I believe its a thermal diode) to keep it from frying if the cooler fails.<br>
Considering I've had many AMD's over the last 4 years and not one has fried, I wouldn't sweat that part.<br>
<br>
Another thing you need to consider Mismort is that its already been stated by Sony that EQ will support 'enchancements' for P4 users.  If you trust what they say that might be a deciding factor for going intel.<br>
<br>
Then again, if you go intel you'll be tacking on another $400 dollars to the price tag since you'll need a more expensive motherboard, more expensive rambus memory, and a more expensive CPU.  If your friend is going to do video editing, P4 should be your choice.  If its an EQ machine, I'd still stick with AMD.<br>
<br>
For hard drives 2 isn't going to make that much of a difference over 1.  And if you get 2 drives you'll need to attach them to different IDE buses to get the most use out of them.  Personally if you are going for a speed demon you might consider getting a cheap LSI or adaptec pci scsi adapter and get a 10k speed scsi drive.  They will move data at least twice as fast as an IDE drive.  But they cost about 3x as much. &lt;shrug&gt;<br>
<br>
A RAID system is only worth it in speed terms if you're going to need to have fault tolerant data.  Even set to striping mode the raid will not perform as well as a single drive setup.<br>
<br>
I agree with Tov on the viewsonic monitors - I have a professional 22&quot; cad model at home and it rocks!  I also have a cheaper 21&quot; model they make and its still great.  And listen to him about the Gainward series Ti500.  THG rated it highly.<br>
<br>
Go Klipsch over Bose.  Bose speakers are so damn overpriced for their quality its sickening.<br>
<br>
